Patrick and Connie were planning on meeting Bob, Julie, Sam, Alyssa in Humpy Cove on Saturday after a Stinson Extended family visit.  Patrick and Connie were waiting to hear from the others about when/if it would occur. Patrick learned through Connie that both Bob and Julie changed the day to Friday. Patrick had previously made it clear that he had to work Friday and could only do Saturday.  The others did not seem to consider this, did not tell him of the day change, and were suprised when he told them he couldn't go.

Patrick was very angry because this was one of many times when they had changed plans without telling him or without talking to him.  Other examples are them not giving him airplane itineraries or letting him know when someone is arriving and leaving Alaska despite his asking several times. Patrick concluded that they function as their own unit that does not include him,  and he should not make attempts to be part of that unit. It is too painful to have the expectations mismatched with their behavior.

items.notes:
Patrick and Bob both headed to Seward. Patrick notices a marked increase Bob's positivity toward him; laughing at his jokes more, using more affirmative language, talking more about the positive sides of things, telling jokes more. 

This looks like a toward from Bob to Patrick. This is a shift from Bob's typical reclusive/negative position. This increased towards is mostly not based on triangling, they are actually relating on things that pertain to them.

Though there is still important question of what other triangles could be pushing these two together without those triangles showing up verbally.

Patrick is aware of his basic pattern of away and negativity toward his mother. Visits with his mother are still quite a bit more stressful.

Patrick is putting continual effort into maintaining self amidst this pattern of increasing towards from his Father. He observes himself slightly slipping into the negative/distant mode in reciprocation. Though all and all this is progressing well.

Patrick is still much more away from Julie. Though they have some pseudo-toward.

items.notes:
- Bob and his friends arrive in Seward for their annual "Seniors" boat trip. Bob's boat may not work for the trip and he behaves as though he can decide to use Patrick's boat without consulting Patrick first. This showed up as Bob quickly saying "Can I use Mambo, OK thanks." He said this in front of his friends in a way meant to pass it off as a joke or no big deal but also that he was serious about using it.

Bob is invested emotionally in the boat and sometimes pays for parts without asking. Patrick is fine with this, though is unclear about whether this is just Father paying for Son's things like insisting on pickup up a tab at dinner, or if Bob assumes he has more ownership over the boat that Patrick does. Patrick intends for this to be his boat which is why he paid for it. Patrick has not yet clearly defined this clearly to Bob. Patrick took a day to think through how to verbally define/clarify his boundaries with the boat. This effort was certainly anxiety driven and the anxiety was pushing to let Bob do what he wanted without clearing it with Patrick just to keep things calm. Bob's flippant manner of "asking" to use the boat indicated that he was also anxious about asking to use it.

Patrick eventually decided that his principle for his boat was that he would enjoy for Bob to make use of the boat as much as possible but he had to clear it with Patrick first. This was difficult for Patrick to do.

The move:

All of the friends were in the living room at one moment talking about their plans. Everyone was drinking alcohol except patrick and Mark P. Patrick waited for a lull in the discussion and:

- Patrick: "Well, I'm just wondering how you are going to get me back to Seward." 
- Bob "What do you mean?"
- Patrick (in playful tone): "Isn't it obvious?"
(quiet....snickers from Bob's friends.)
- Bob (in serious tone): "I don't think you understand..."
- Patrick (in serious tone): "Look, if you are going to take Mambo then I get to choose whether to come with."
- Bob's friend Mark P. laughed a little. He was also present for a similar define-self move by Patrick to Bob the previous summer when he, Patrick, and Bob were racing the boat. That was the first of its kind.
- Bob (under his breath): "We'll find a way to get you back."

Some anxiety was left over for Patrick after this move. He sent a text to Bob (Bob was quite stressed/busy doing errands) that he was more than welcome to take the boat but that they needed to chat about it first. Bob called later and Patrick told Bob in a clear and strong voice that Patrick would love for him to use the boat (it took effort to get neutral about that), but that he would have to check with Patrick first. For example, you never know the state of the boat or if it is in the middle of a project. Bob agreed and Patrick felt resolution. Stating his boundary as a matter of fact instead of a suggestion or mere request defined Patrick's position as owner of his own boat with his Father.

The anxiety and togetherness of this long-standing annual guy's trip made this a more intense episode than normal. Bob would have been more considerate and less urgent under normal circumstances. But this extreme case was an opportunity to define self amidst one of the most intense togetherness contexts available.

items.notes:
Bob calls patrick for a second time to ask him to come over for a potluck dinner because "He hasn't seen Nicole."

Patrick is aware of the triangle but having a hard time figuring out how to detriangle. He doesn't respond to the bit about Nicole but says he will come over when he can. Patrick is annoyed at there being no notice of these events though this is typical. 

While writing this log entry Patrick decides to tell his dad he can't make it tonight. Rationale is of the short notice and it being driven by the triangle from Bob/Nicole to Patrick. He recognizes the change of plans is causing him stress and thinks it is the triangle.  Patrick texts Bob saying

"On second look I can’t make it tonight. Too hard to change plans on short notice. Have fun. I’ll drop your snowblower tomorrow."

He does not mention Nicole but thinks he should be prepared to address the triangle kick-back again via Bob.  Later He decides his principle in play is that he does not change plans of consequence with short notice - especially if the person in question did not tell him directly.
